<h1>Experiment 1: Latent Zero-Out Test</h1>
<p class="subtitle">Independently zero out each branch's latent to quantify unique contribution</p>

<div class="card">
<h3>Quantitative Results</h3>
<table>
<tr><th>Model</th><th>Normal PSNR</th><th>Zero-Temporal</th><th>Zero-Spatial</th><th>Temporal Drop</th><th>Spatial Drop</th></tr>
<tr><td>8×/C4</td><td>31.36 dB</td><td>12.08 dB</td><td>27.61 dB</td><td class="highlight">−19.28 dB</td><td>−3.75 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>16×/C16</td><td>32.67 dB</td><td>27.11 dB</td><td>14.24 dB</td><td>−5.56 dB</td><td class="highlight">−18.43 dB</td></tr>
<tr><td>32×/C16</td><td>27.54 dB</td><td>24.62 dB</td><td>15.47 dB</td><td>−2.92 dB</td><td class="highlight">−12.08 dB</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Key finding:</strong> The two branches carry non-redundant, complementary information. In 8×/C4, the temporal branch dominates; in 16×/C16 and 32×/C16, the spatial branch dominates — governed by channel allocation.</p>
